<br But when parents arrive at the hospital, do they notice that there is a problem?<br> When they arrive in the emergency room, the situation is quite compromised. Sometimes it happens that parents do not notice what their children do. I got an anecdote. Last summer I was visiting a girl wearing a heavy sweatshirt, although in those days in Rome it was very hot. Speaking to her and trying to establish a relationship of reciprocity, I invited her to parade the sweatshirt. Taking off the sweatshirt, the mother who was sitting next to her is pale. The girl had her arms covered with scars,» she had been practicing self-harm for a long time. But the most terrible thing was this girl's sentence by turning to her mother 'it was him because you knew what I've been doing for a long time'. I have the impression that parents are very disrespectful and also happy to delegate educational activity to others or others, such as smarphone. This book “Adolescents interrupted” means that life can resume, but it serves an effort from the adult community to be there and ensure an emotional presence. Kids today complain solitude and often the only form of company are virtual chats.&nbsp;
How long are we gonna say it's pandemic? > The pandemic has certainly been a devastating moment, but it has amplified a phenomenon already present. Actually, the big increase in mental disorders has been seeing him since 2010 onwards. Prior to 2020, first aid access cases had increased considerably. In 2010, a well-known brand of telephony markets the first smartphone with integrated camera and therefore the possibility to take selfies and then in 2013 the prices of mobile phones collapse, becoming the gift of the first communion. There is no doubt that there is a relationship between anxiety and depression disorders that are so increased among teenagers and uncontrolled use of electronic instruments.&nbsp;
How much do you invest in mental health in Italy? > In mental health very little and in the health of minors I would say zero. It's impressive. The data are known to all and there is no initiative in this direction. The National Health Service is in great suffering and I would say we are really at a difficult time. That's why I felt the need to tell her these things because you didn't say 'I didn't know'.&nbsp;
What was your younger patient? > The youngest girl we admitted for trying suicide was 9 years old.&nbsp;
<br In these days we talk a lot about the death of Andrea Prospero, the suicide boy in Perugia, also victim of a “mortal” chat. So it's not just teens who end up victims of web isolation.&nbsp;><br> Adolescence in biological terms ends at 25 years. So it is a whole age group that lives the same moment of deep crisis and isolation. &nbsp;
<br But should I use devices with minors?><br> Your smartphone should be prohibited. A child should not see TV before 5 years independently. The smarphone should never be given to a child, independently, before the 12 years and even after a time limit is placed and under the control of the parents. Another theme is sleep hours. Today children and teens sleep much less and often late to follow TV or because they use smartphones. Sleeping little threatens mental health, is a critical aspect. If we want to take care of mental health, we must educate our children to eat and sleep well, at times at their age. I mean, parents must be educators.&nbsp;
<br What advice does it feel to give parents? > I recommend that families be there, to be there, not to think that children can do it on their own. Promote their autonomy, help them from children to sleep alone, eat alone, dress up, go to school, do their homework, promote sports activities to grow them in an open environment. Give rules, say no and do not worry about their suffering in front of a ban. Being, watching them, almost spying on them. Being silent can encourage their request for help and be attentive to changes, to the signals of malaise that may be protracted for weeks and months. Don't be ashamed to ask professional operators for help. &nbsp;
